  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically addressed under criminal legislation. In many jurisdictions, money laundering is considered a serious financial crime that involves:\n\n1. Concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n2. Transforming \"dirty\" money from criminal activities into seemingly \"clean\" funds\n3. Making illegally obtained money appear legitimate\n\nSpecific legal approaches to money laundering vary between countries, but it is generally prosecuted under:\n- Criminal codes\n- Anti-money laundering (AML) statutes\n- Financial crime legislation\n- Proceeds of crime laws\n\nPenalties can include:\n- Substantial fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- Financial sanctions\n\nMost developed countries have strict legal frameworks and regulatory mechanisms to prevent and prosecute money laundering activities.",
